Put two large #saucepans{} of water, each with a generous pinch of @salt{pinch}, on to boil for the potatoes and beans. Chop the @salad potatoes{350%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel) and pop them in one of your pans of boiling water. Cook for ~{12-17%minutes}.

> TIP: The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{150%g}. Pick the @tarragon{1/4%bunch} leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks).

Pat the @coley fillet{2} dry with #kitchen paper{}. Season the fish with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat a splash of @oil{a splash} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the pan is hot, add the fish. Fry for ~{4-5%minutes}, then, carefully turn and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} more.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

Remove it from the pan, set aside and cover with #foil{} to keep warm. Keep the pan - we'll use it again!

While the fish cooks, pop the green beans in your second pan of boiling water. Cook for ~{4%minutes}, then drain in a #colander{} and put to one side. Boil your #kettle{}, then pour the @water{150%ml}(boiling) into a #measuring jug{} with the @vegetable stock powder{1/2%tsp}. Stir to dissolve, ready for the tarragon sauce.

Once the cod is out of your frying pan, add the stock to your pan on medium-high heat. Boil until it has reduced by one-third, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove from the heat and pour in the @creme fraiche{75%g}. Give it a good stir, then add the tarragon (don't use it all if you only want a subtle flavour). Season to taste with salt and pepper if needed.

When the potatoes are cooked, drain in your colander and allow to steam-dry for ~{1%minute} (you want as much water to drain out as possible). Return them to the pan and lightly crush with the back of a #fork{}. For a decadent finish, toss them in a knob of @butter{1%knob}(if you have some) and a pinch of salt and pepper.

Divide the crushed new potatoes and green beans between your plates. Top with the cod and finish with a generous amount of tarragon sauce. Enjoy!